Mets€a-Ketel€a, Department of Biochemistry, University of Turku, FIN-20014 Turku, Finland Fax: +35 823 336 860 Tel: +35 823 336 847 E-mail: mikko.mk@gmail.com *Present address: Department of Biosciences, (cid:2)Abo Akademi University, Turku, Finland (Received 1 April 2014, revised 26 June 2014, accepted 30 July 2014) Pseudouridine (Fig. 1) is a nonclassical nucleoside that is a universal constituent of RNAs in all three domains of life [1]. It is present in all structural RNAs and, for instance, the mammalian ribosomal RNA contains ~ 100 pseudouridines per ribosome [2]. The difference in the chemical structures of uridine and pseudouridine resides in the glycosyl bond that links the uracil base to the canonical uridine nucleosides are connected through an N5–C10 bond, pseudouridine contains an unusual C5–C10 arrange- the ment, which alters the chemical properties of Abbreviations EcYeiN, E. coli YeiN; PsiMP, pseudouridine-50-phosphate; TmYeiN, T. maritima YeiN. FEBS Journal 281 (2014) 4439–4449 ª 2014 FEBS

Pseudouridine is a noncanonical C–nucleoside commonly present in RNA, which is not metabolized in mammals, but can be recycled by the unique enzyme family of bacterial pseudouridine glycosidases such as YeiN from Escherichia coli. Here, we present rigorous bioinformatic and biochemical analyses of the protein family in order to ﬁnd sequences that might code for nonpseudouridine glycosidase activities. To date, the only other func- tion reported for the enzyme family occurs during the biosynthesis of the antibiotic alnumycin A in Streptomyces species, where AlnA functions as an unusual C–glycosynthase. Bioinformatics analysis of 755 protein sequences identiﬁed one group of sequences that were unlikely to harbour pseudouridine glycosidase activities. This observation was conﬁrmed in vitro with one representative protein, IdgA from Streptomyces albus, which was unable to synthesize pseudouridine monophosphate, but was able to attach D–ribose-5-phosphate to juglone. Furthermore, our analyses provide evi- dence for horizontal gene transfer of pseudouridine glycosidases that may have occurred in Streptomyces and Doria species. Inspection of the geno- mic loci in the vicinity of pseudouridine glycosidases revealed that in 77% of the strains a kinase gene putatively involved in the phosphorylation of pseudouridine was found nearby, whereas the sequences encoding non- pseudouridine glycosidases coexisted with a phosphatase of the haloacid dehalogenase enzyme family. The investigation suggested that these unknown sequences might be involved in the biosynthesis of soluble blue pigments because of the presence of genes homologous to nonribosomal peptide synthetases. nucleoside because the free N5–H may act as an addi- tional hydrogen bond donor. Over the years, pseudo- uridine has been connected with a number of biological roles, but a role in the stabilization of higher order RNA structures through enhanced base stacking has been widely recognized [1].

Because of the abundance of pseudouridine it is not surprising that many organisms are able to recycle the metabolite identiﬁed the enzymes that are involved in the catabolism of the nucleoside [2]. Experiments conducted with proteins Analysis of pseudouridine-50-phosphate glycosidases the pseudouridine kinase YeiC and the PsiMP glycosidase YeiN involved in the degradation of Fig. 1. Reactions catalysed by (A) pseudouridine in E. coli, and (B) the C–glycosynthase AlnA and the phosphatase AlnB that participate in the biosynthesis of alnumycin A in Streptomyces sp. CM020. from the uropathogenic Escherichia coli UT189 have shown that the ﬁrst step on the pathway is the phos- phorylation of pseudouridine by the kinase YeiC (Fig. 1A). Of especial interest for this study is the sec- ond enzyme on the pathway, YeiN (hereafter denoted EcYeiN), which is able to hydrolyse the glycosidic C5– C10 bond and convert pseudouridine-50-phosphate (PsiMP) to uracil and D-ribose-5-phosphate (Fig. 1A). In addition to EcYeiN, the homologous enzyme IndA (hereafter denoted TmYeiN) from Thermotoga mariti- ma has been shown to act as a PsiMP glycosidase [2]. Determination of the crystal structure of TmYeiN from T. maritima revealed that the protein has a novel aba fold, where the central mixed b sheet is ﬂanked by six and seven a helices on each side [3]. Crystallo- graphic snapshots of EcYeiN identiﬁed a lysine adduct during catalysis and revealed the mechanistic impor- tance of Schiff base formation between Lys166 and C– 1 of the ring-opened ribose [4]. These key studies together with the unique fold and sequence conserva- tion have enabled the identiﬁcation of a small new enzyme family of PsiMP glycosidases.

The investigations mentioned above have led to the annotation of all of the members of the protein family as PsiMP glycosidases in public databases such as Pfam [5]. However, our previous studies into the bio- synthesis of an unusual polyketide antibiotic alnumy- (Fig. 1B) produced by Streptomyces sp. cin A [6,7] CM020 have uncovered that not all members of the protein family are true PsiMP glycosidases [8,9]. We have shown that the initial step in the formation of the unusual 40–hydroxy-50-hydroxymethyl-20,70-dioxane unit of alnumycin A is the attachment of D–ribose-5- phosphate to the prealnumycin aglycone by AlnA, an enzyme homologous to EcYeiN and TmYeiN [9]. One key difference between these enzymes resides in direc- tionality: EcYeiN and YmYeiN are catabolic enzymes pseudouridine-5'-phosphate that cleave a glycosidic carbon–carbon bond (although the reaction may proceed in the opposite direction [2], whereas AlnA is a C–glycosynthase in vitro) involved in antibiotic biosynthesis [9]. The sequence homology indicates towards a common evolutionary origin for these enzymes and it is likely that AlnA has evolved from ancestral PsiMP glycosidases by adopt- ing prealnumycin as a ligand instead of uracil (Fig. 1). The second step is the dephosphorylation of the AlnA reaction product, alnumycin P, by AlnB [9], an enzyme of the haloacid dehalogenase superfamily [10]. The generation of the dioxane unit then requires two fur- ther biosynthetic steps [8].

The aim of this study was to conduct rigorous bioin- formatic and biochemical analyses of enzymes homolo- gous to YeiN and AlnA to investigate whether the protein family contains other members that code for non-PsiMP glycosidase activities. Comparative phyloge- netic analysis of 219 bacterial members of the family revealed three clades of sequences that did not appear to conform to the evolution of the bacterial species. Exper- imental work with six proteins conﬁrmed that IdgA from Streptomyces albus did not harbour any PsiMP glycosidase activity, but was able to act as a C–glyco- synthase in a manner similar to AlnA [11]. Inspection of the organization of the genomic loci of the non-PsiMP these enzymes glycosidase sequences suggested that might be involved in the biosynthesis of blue pigments. Phylogenetic analysis of putative PsiMP glycosidases A total of 755 sequences of bacterial origin homologous to YeiN and AlnA were retrieved from the Pfam data- base [5]. The number was reduced to 250 unique FEBS Journal 281 (2014) 4439–4449 ª 2014 FEBS sequences after removal of sequences with > 90% sequence identity using the program CD–HIT [12]. The phylogenetic tree shown in Fig. 2 was constructed using the neighbour joining method [13] from a multiple sequence alignment as described in the Experimental Procedures and colour-coded based on the various bac- terial families. However, the separation of the different bacterial families did not appear robust, as indicated by the low bootstrap values in many of the clades signifying that PsiMP glycosidase sequences were Analysis of pseudouridine-50-phosphate glycosidases Analysis of pseudouridine-50-phosphate glycosidases

not optimal as a marker gene for bacterial evolution. Of the various bacterial families, the sequences obtained from a–Proteobacteria (red), b–Proteobacteria (yellow), c–Proteobacteria (orange), Thermotogaceae (olive) and the main clade of Actinobacteria (dark green) were best resolved, whereas especially the main clade of Firmi- cutes (blue) were mixed with various other sequences. Both of the conﬁrmed PsiMP glycosidases EcYeiN and TmYeiN were positioned correctly in the c–Proteobac- teria and Thermotogaceae clades (Fig. S1), respectively. The most intriguing aspect of the phylogenetic tree was the observation of three groups of sequences (Fig. 2, coloured boxes) that were clearly separated into their own clades (100% bootstrap values), but anoma- lously positioned in terms of their origin. The sequences in Group I were derived from b–Proteobacteria (yel- low), c–Proteobacteria (orange) and Actinobacteria (dark green), and were positioned close to the sequence of the C–glycosynthase AlnA. Group II contained a small portion of (dark green) sequences mixed with about half of the sequences from Deinococcus thermos (grey). Finally, a portion of the sequences (blue) were positioned abnormally a long distance away from all of the other sequences and were designated as Group III. Comparative phylogenetic analysis

In order to obtain further evidence that the sequences in the three outlier groups might have deviated from the evolution of the bacterial species, we compiled a second phylogenetic tree from 16S rDNA sequences that were obtained from the same bacterial species. The 16S rDNA tree (Fig. 3) demonstrated improved resolution in comparison to the PsiMP glycosidase tree and the sequences were well-positioned in the correct bacterial phyla. As an example, all of the sequences from Deinococcus thermos (grey) and Actinobacteria (dark green) were now found within a single clade in the 16S rDNA tree. Importantly, this also included the sequences that were identiﬁed as outliers in the analy- sis of the PsiMP glycosidase sequences. The results thus suggested that the sequences in Groups I–III were either: (a) true PsiMP glycosidases that had been hori- zontally transferred from other bacterial species or (b) they might represent proteins that catalyse hitherto unknown reactions. Analysis of the surrounding genomic loci of the outlier genes To continue the characterization of the unknown sequences residing in Groups I to III, we performed

MultiGeneBlast analysis [14] to reveal the possible simi- larities and dissimilarities in the genomic content adja- cent to the query sequences. The conﬁrmed PsiMP glycosidases from E. coli and T. maritima, respectively, contain a kinase in the same operon [2], whereas the C– glycosynthase alnA is translationally coupled to a phos- phatase alnB of the haloacid dehalogenase family [6]. Overall, the presence of a kinase homologous to yeiC from E. coli could be detected in 77.6% of the 219 strains analysed indicating that the absence of a kinase was not completely indicative for non-PsiMP glycosi- dase activity. As an example, the sequences obtained from b–Proteobacteria Group II (Fig. 4, yellow) did not co-exist with a kinase. Nonetheless, it is noteworthy that none of the sequences allocated to outlier Group I (Fig. 4) contained a kinase in the vicinity of the puta- tive PsiMP glycosidases, but rather harboured a phos- phatase in the majority of strains in a manner similar to the alnumycin gene cluster. The analysis further revealed that all of these gene clusters also contained a gene homologous to nonribosomal peptide synthetases that have been implicated in the biosynthesis of the blue pigment indigoidine [15,16]. Other genes that appeared to be highly conserved were similar to phospho- ribosyltransferases and 4–oxalocrotonate tautomerases (Fig. 4, Group I). By contrast, the outlier sequences from Deinococcus thermos (grey) and Actinobacteria (dark green) in Group II were all preceded by a kinase gene (Fig. 4) suggesting that these gene products might encode true PsiMP glycosidases acquired through hori- zontal gene transfer. This was also the case with the sequences residing in Group III where a kinase was found in all cases except one (Fig. 4). Experimental analysis of the outlier proteins

Next, we proceeded to conﬁrm the bioinformatics analyses results by testing the activities of selected in vitro. The putative PsiMP glycosidases enzymes originating from S. albus J1074 (IdgA, Group I), Streptomyces himastatinicus ATTC 53653 (ShYeiN, Group II), Burkholderia sp. H160 (BsYeiN, Group II) and Dorea formicigenerans ATCC 27755 (DfYeiN, Group III) were produced and puriﬁed together with EcYeiN and AlnA in E. coli as described in the Exper- imental Procedures. The proteins were then tested for PsiMP glycosidase activity (Fig. 1A) and for their abil- ity to attach a D–ribose-5-phosphate unit to juglone (Fig. 5A), which has recently been identiﬁed as a pro- miscuous enzymatic activity of AlnA [11]. Analysis of reaction mixtures by HPLC conﬁrmed that BsYeiN, ShYeiN, DfYeiN were true PsiMP glycosidases, whereas IdgA and AlnA were unable to FEBS Journal 281 (2014) 4439–4449 ª 2014 FEBS Fig. 3. utilize uracil as a substrate (Fig. 6A). By contrast, IdgA was the only enzyme in addition to AlnA which was juglone (Fig. 6B), but only under reduced oxygen concentra- tions, as documented previously for AlnA [8]. The PsiMP glycosidase activity could be performed in both the presence and absence of molecular oxygen. The phosphorylated IdgA/AlnA reaction products could be converted to the ﬁnal C–ribosylated compounds by AlnB or the homologous IdgB from the indigoidine FEBS Journal 281 (2014) 4439–4449 ª 2014 FEBS capable of phosphoribosylation of gene cluster of S. albus (Fig. S2). Finally, the blue pig- ment indigoidine (Fig. 5B) was examined as a sub- strate for IdgA and IdgB, but no enzymatic activity was detected (data not shown). Fig. 5. Possible reactions catalysed by IdgA and IdgB from S. albus. The enzymes were conﬁrmed to be able to (A) attach a ribose unit to juglone, although (B) the blue pigment indigoidine was not accepted as a substrate. We speculate that (C) the enzymes might be involved in the biosynthesis of the soluble pigment indochrome B1. [1]. During the degradation of RNA, pseudouridine-50- phosphate is converted to pseudouridine [17], but mammals are not capable in processing the nucleoside further and the metabolite is excreted in urine [18]. Therefore, it is not surprising that many bacteria and some eukaryotes are able to utilize pseudouridine as a carbon and nitrogen source, and catabolize the metab- olite with the help of a pseudouridine kinase YeiC and PsiMP glycosidase YeiN [2]. The unusual C–C glyco- sidic bond of PsiMP is not hydrolysed as easily as the canonical O-glycosidic bond, and, in effect, the enzyme responsible for the reaction is not similar in structure or fold to any other proteins [3,4].

Our analyses here indicate that the majority (96%) of the bacterial protein sequences belonging to this dis- tinct enzyme family are true PsiMP glycosidases and only in few cases do the enzymes appear to have evolved further to catalyse other reactions. Many bac- terial strains seem to harbour the kinase gene required for degradation of pseudouridine in the vicinity of the PsiMP glycosidase genes in a manner similar to yeiC and yeiN in E. coli: this was found to occur in 77.6% of cases after analysis of 219 genome sequences. How- ever, the coexistence appears to depend upon the bac- terial family and is not essential as demonstrated by the b–Proteobacteria clade (Fig. 2, yellow), where the orphan gene product BsYeiN from Burkholderia sp. H160 was shown to exhibit PsiMP glycosidase activity. The comparative phylogenetic analysis of PsiMP gly- cosidases and 16s rDNA sequences provides evidence that some bacterial strains may have acquired the FEBS Journal 281 (2014) 4439–4449 ª 2014 FEBS phosphoribosylated juglone PsiMP glycosidase via horizontal gene transfer. These include sequences obtained from Deinococcus thermos (Group II, Fig. 2), Actinobacteria (Group II, Fig. 2) and Firmicutes (Group III, Fig. 2). It is somewhat sur- prising that DfYeiN exhibited PsiMP glycosidase activ- ity, because in sequences of Group III (Fig. 2) reside a great evolutionary distance from the other PsiMP glycosidases. Inspection of the multiple sequence alignment reveals that an important factor in separation of these sequences is the deletion of 8–14 amino acids that correspond to helix a8 in AlnA [9]. This helical segment resides away from the active site on the other side of the protein and may be involved in protein–protein interactions with helix a4 from another subunit of the AlnA trimer (Fig. S3). Accord- ingly, numerous amino acid substitutions have occurred in the a4 region of DfYeiN in comparison to the other PsiMP glycosidases.

The phylogenetic analysis uncovered one particular group of sequences (Group I, Fig. 2) in which the enzy- matic activity appears to have diversiﬁed. This clade contains AlnA, which has been conﬁrmed to act as a C– glycosynthase in the biosynthesis of the polyketide anti- biotic alnumycin A [8,9]. Here, we demonstrate that both AlnA and IdgA lack PsiMP glycosidase activity, but share the promiscuous activity of AlnA, the attach- ment of D–ribose-5-phosphate to juglone [11]. The HAD-phosphatases AlnB and IdgB are then able to the C–ribosylation process, subsequently complete strongly suggesting that IdgA and IdgB are involved in the biosynthesis of an as yet unknown natural product. Analysis of pseudouridine-50-phosphate glycosidases Analysis of pseudouridine-50-phosphate glycosidases Fig. 6. HPLC traces of in vitro reactions with (A) uracil and (B) juglone as substrates recorded at 280 and 425 nm, respectively. The previously conﬁrmed reactions of EcYeiN with D–ribose-5- phosphate and uracil [2,4], and AlnA with D–ribose-5-phosphate and juglone [11] serve as positive controls for the enzymatic reactions, whereas the negative control reactions (uracil and juglone) were performed in the absence of enzymes. The substrate juglone is not visible in the HPLC chromatograms because the reaction mixtures were extracted with chloroform during sample preparation and only the phosphoribosylated reaction product of AlnA and IdgA may be detected from the water phase analysed by HPLC. In addition, the phosphoribosylated juglone is not stable and dephosphorylates to juglone C–ribosylate also nonenzymatically [11]. These compounds may be separated from each other partially (see Fig. S2).

The close proximity and conservation of nonribosomal peptide synthetase genes responsible for the formation of indigoidine would suggest that IdgA and IdgB might be involved in modiﬁcation of this insoluble blue pig- ment. However, because enzymatic activity could not be detected with indigoidine, we speculate that the sub- strate of IdgA may, in effect, be the monomer unit of the compound (Fig. 5C). The mechanism of indigoidine formation remains unclear, but it is likely that the prod- uct of the nonribosomal peptide synthetases is a mono- mer intermediate that is dimerised and oxidized to generate the blue pigment [17]. The beneﬁt of our hypothesis is that: (a) the indigoidine monomer would be compatible with the mechanisms proposed for AlnA and YeiN, and (b) the substrate would be more similar in size to uracil rather than the bulkier indigoidine. In addition, an early C–ribosylation step would be better suited to explain the formation of the soluble pigment indochrome B1 (Fig. 5C), which has been isolated from Arthrobacter polychromogenes over four decades ago [19]. Other than indochrome B1, we note that enzymes of the PsiMP glycosidase family might be involved in the biosynthesis of certain C–nucleotide antibiotics [20– 23], which contain C–glycosidally linked ribose units. Investigations into the formation of these metabolites are currently in progress in our laboratory. Sequence retrieval and selection The AlnA sequence (313 amino acids, Uniprot identiﬁer B6SEG5) was used as a query in the search for homologous protein sequences using FASTA against the Pfam database [5], which resulted in 755 redundant amino acid sequences. CD-HIT [12] was utilized to remove identical protein sequences and sequences with > 90% identity to facilitate the computa- tional and manual editing tasks. Subsequently, a total of 379 nonredundant sequences were obtained. Additional manual FEBS Journal 281 (2014) 4439–4449 ª 2014 FEBS

editing in the sequence editor BioEdit [24] was required to remove distantly related sequences that could not be aligned with conﬁdence in multiple sequence alignment due to great variation in length (> 410 or < 73 amino acids) resulting in 250 sequences ready for further analysis. All of the 16S rDNA sequences were retrieved individu- ally from the [25]. The sequences were collected from the same bacterial strains from which the PsiMP glycosidase sequences originated with few exceptions (e.g. this data was unavailable for the strain from which the AlnA sequence originates). Taxo- nomic lineage was used as a reference to ensure the right strains while downloading the 16S rDNA sequences from the ribosomal database. A total of 219 sequences were selected for further study. Multiple sequence alignment and phylogenetic trees Multiple sequence alignment was performed using MUSCLE [26] integrated within SEAVIEW v. 4 [27], a multiplatform graphical user interface for sequence alignment and phylo- genetic tree construction. Phylogenetic trees were generated using the distance-based neighbour-joining [13] method in SEAVIEW platform assigning bootstrap value [28] of 100. As a result, rooted trees were generated based on the complete set of sequences of the PsiMP glycosidase enzyme family. The phylogenetic trees were colour-coded according to the bacterial classiﬁcation system using the tree-viewing pro- gram FIGTREE.

The total of 34 PsiMP glycosidases identiﬁed as outlier sequences were divided into three groups and the neigh- bouring genomic loci was analysed using MultiGeneBlast. Architecture search method was preferred as it helps to reveal the composition of genomic content of the neigh- bouring loci adjacent to the query sequence [14]. To exe- cute the MultiGeneBlast searches, 34 separate input ﬁles in fasta format were created containing the PsiMP sequence with 10 surrounding neighbouring genes (ﬁve forwards and ﬁve backwards) using the JALVIEW program [29]. Each input ﬁle was run against a corresponding MultiGeneBlast data- base constructed manually from the genome sequences of the 34 selected strains. The graphical representation of the characterized gene clusters was prepared on the basis of the outputs of the combined MultiGeneBlast search runs. Bacterial strains and culture conditions Escherichia coli TOP10 (Invitrogen, Carlsbad, CA, USA) was used for both cloning and protein production purposes. The strain was cultivated in Luria–Bertani medium supple- FEBS Journal 281 (2014) 4439–4449 ª 2014 FEBS ribosomal database project mented with 100 lg(cid:2)mL(cid:3)1 of ampicillin for the production of plasmid DNA and His-tagged EcYeiN. For the produc- tion of all other proteins, 29 yeast extract/tryptone medium supplemented with 50 lg(cid:2)mL(cid:3)1 of ampicillin was used.

The ORF yeiN from E. coli was ampliﬁed by PCR using Phusion polymerase (Thermo Scientiﬁc, Lafayette, CO, USA) with boiled cells of strain K12 as a template. The nucleotide sequence of the forward primer yeiNforB was CTAGATCTGAATTAAAAATTTCCCCTGAATTATTA CAAATT, and the sequence of the reverse primer yeiN- revH was CATAAGCTTAACCCGCGAGACGCTGATA TT. The PCR product was digested with the restriction endonucleases BglII and HindIII and ligated with a simi- larly digested, modiﬁed pBADHisB (Invitrogen, Carlsbad, CA, USA) vector pBADHisBD [30]. The open reading frames idgA and idgB from S. albus J1074, and the yeiN ORFs from Burkholderia sp. H160, Dorea formicigenerns ATCC 27755 and Streptomyces himastatinicus ATCC 53653 were ordered from GeneArt as synthetic genes with codons optimized for expression in E. coli. The synthetic DNA was digested with BglII and HindIII, and ligated into a similarly cut pBADHisBD vector for protein pro- duction. The constructs were veriﬁed by sequencing. Production and puriﬁcation of proteins

Protein production was induced at D600 = 0.5–0.7 with 0.02– 0.04% (w/v) L–arabinose, after which the cultures were grown at room temperature overnight. The cells were washed once and lysed using French Press. The His-tagged proteins were then puriﬁed in a single step using Talon Cobalt resin (Clontech, Mountain View, CA, USA). Both the lysis and the equilibration stages were conducted on ice in 50 mM He- pes (pH 7), 100 mM NaCl (300 mM NaCl for His–YeiN), 5 mM imidazole and 10% (w/v) glycerol. The proteins were then eluted on ice with a similar buffer containing 300 mM (500 mM for His–YeiN). The buffer was imidazole exchanged into 50 mM Hepes pH 7, 100 mM NaCl, 5 mM MgCl2 and 10% glycerol using a PD–10 desalting column (Amersham, Piscataway, NJ, USA). For His–YeiN, the buf- fer was exchanged into 25 mM Hepes pH 7, 25 mM KCl and 10% glycerol. All protein preparations were diluted 1 : 1 in glycerol before freezing, and the purity was estimated by SDS/PAGE analysis. The protein concentrations were calcu- lated based on the absorbance at 280 nm. The reactions were incubated in 25 mM Hepes pH 7, 50 mM NaCl, 2.5 mM MgCl2 for 120 min at room temperature (AlnA and AlnB) or at +30 °C (all other proteins). When Analysis of pseudouridine-50-phosphate glycosidases Analysis of pseudouridine-50-phosphate glycosidases

necessary, oxygen concentration was reduced with the glu- cose oxidase system as described previously [8]. The AlnA/ IdgA/YeiN concentration was 50 lM, and the AlnB/IdgB concentration was 5 lM. The concentrations of the substrates were: 10 mM D–ribose-5-phosphate disodium salt hydrate (98%, Sigma-Aldrich, St. Louis, MO, USA), 0.5 mM juglone (5-hydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone, 97%, Sigma-Aldrich) and 1 mM uracil (99%, Sigma-Aldrich). The reactions were quenched by extracting three times with chloroform (1 : 1 volume). HPLC analysis of the reaction products

The compounds extracted from the enzymatic reactions with uracil or juglone as substrates were analysed by RP- HPLC (Shimadzu VP series chromatography system with a diode array detector SPD-M10Avp) with a Phenomenex Synergy Fusion-RP (4 lM, 4.6 9 150 mm) or a Supelco Discovery C-18 (5 lM, 4.6 9 50 mm) column, respectively. For analysis of PsiMP and uracil, a gradient from 60 mM ammonium acetate (pH 3.6) to 50% acetonitrile was uti- lized with a ﬂow rate of 1 mL(cid:2)min(cid:3)1, while in the case of juglone, phosphoribosylated juglone and ribosylated jug- lone, a gradient from 2% methanol in 60 mM ammonium acetate buffer (pH 3.6) to 100% MeOH was used with a ﬂow rate of 0.5 mL(cid:2)min(cid:3)1. The identiﬁcation of PsiMP and (phospho)ribosylated juglone were based on the previously established enzymatic activities of EcYeiN in the presence of D–ribose-5-phosphate and uracil [2,4] and AlnA with D– ribose-5-phosphate and juglone [11], respectively.
